>
	<p>Funtown Splashtown USA is Maine's largest combined amusement and water park — roughly 50 rides, water slides, pools, and attractions spread across a single property on Route 1 in Saco. It's about 1.5 miles from Saco Bay Hotel. For families with kids of any age, it's the most complete park in southern Maine — different in character from Palace Playland's beachfront energy, but arguably a better full-day experience for a mixed group.</p>

	<p>The park has been family-owned since 1959 and has a cult following in New England. Here's what to know before you go.</p>

	<h2>The Rides: What Makes This Place Unique</h2>

	<h3>Excalibur — Maine's Only Wooden Roller Coaster</h3>

	<p>Excalibur opened in 1998 and remains the signature attraction: Maine's only wooden roller coaster, and the largest, tallest coaster in the state's history. It also holds the title of <strong>largest wooden coaster in Northern New England</strong>. The coaster winds through the wooded edge of the park — the trees make it feel like it goes on longer than it does. For coaster enthusiasts, this is the reason to visit.</p>

	<p>Best suited for ages 8+. Minimum height: 48 inches to ride alone.</p>

	<h3>Astrosphere — The 1976 Time Capsule</h3>

	<p>Opened in 1976 and changed very little since. A fully enclosed dome combining a Scrambler-style ride with a complete laser light show — and the music is <strong>"Fire on High" by Electric Light Orchestra</strong>, playing on a loop. It's genuinely strange, genuinely beloved, and a rite of passage for anyone who grew up going to Funtown. Don't skip it.</p>

	<h3>Whispering Pines Haunted Hotel Dark Ride</h3>

	<p>The first new ride added to the park in 20 years, opened in 2023, designed by Sally Dark Rides. Guests board custom vehicles (up to four per car) through 14 uniquely themed rooms of a cursed hotel. In 2024 it placed <strong>6th in USA Today's 10Best Reader Choice Awards for Top New Theme Park Attractions in the United States</strong> — not a local honor, a national one. Worth at least one run-through.</p>

	<h3>Thunder Falls Log Flume</h3>

	<p>New England's longest and tallest log flume ride. Virtually guarantees a soaking — bring a change of clothes or embrace being wet for the rest of the day.</p>

	<h2>Splashtown: The Water Park</h2>

	<p>The water park opens approximately mid-June (2025 opening: June 14) and runs through Labor Day. Operating hours: approximately 10:30 AM – 5:00 PM.</p>

	<p><strong>Water slides and features:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Mammoth, Tornado, and Mount Olympus</strong> — the tallest and largest water slides of their kind in Maine</li>
		<li><strong>Amphitrite's Challenge</strong> — a four-lane mat racer slide (head-to-head racing down parallel lanes)</li>
	</ul>

	<p>The water park is a genuine standalone attraction. On a hot August day, some families spend their entire visit here without touching the amusement park side.</p>

	<h2>Season and Hours</h2>

	<p><strong>Funtown (amusement park):</strong> Opens Memorial Day weekend. Hours approximately 10:30 AM – 6:00 PM.</p>

	<p><strong>Splashtown (water park):</strong> Opens mid-June. Hours approximately 10:30 AM – 5:00 PM.</p>

	<p>Both run daily through Labor Day. Special <strong>21+ nights</strong> are offered select Saturday evenings in July and August — a good date-night option for adults.</p>

	<h2>Pricing</h2>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>General Admission (48"+ / adults):</strong> $49.00</li>
		<li><strong>Children under 38":</strong> FREE</li>
		<li><strong>Season Passes:</strong> Big Combo (48"+): $149.95 | Little Combo (38"–48"): $139.95 | Senior Combo (60+): $86.95</li>
	</ul>

	<p>Online advance tickets are often available at a slight discount — worth checking funtownsplashtownusa.com before your visit.</p>

	<h2>Height and Age Guide</h2>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>Under 38":</strong> Free admission; focus on the kiddie rides</li>
		<li><strong>38"–48":</strong> Full access to children's section, Thunder Falls log flume, and the water park; can't ride Excalibur alone</li>
		<li><strong>48"+:</strong> Full access to everything, including Excalibur; the wooden coaster is best for ages 8+</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Tips for Making the Most of Your Day</h2>

	<p><strong>Arrive at opening (10:30 AM).</strong> Excalibur and the Whispering Pines dark ride draw the longest lines by midday. Tackle both immediately after entering, before the crowds build.</p>

	<p><strong>Weekdays are significantly less crowded</strong> than weekends and holidays — particularly Tuesdays and Wednesdays in July. If flexibility exists, visit mid-week.</p>

	<p><strong>Bring a change of clothes.</strong> Thunder Falls and the water park will soak you. There's no polite way to say "you'll be wet for four hours" — plan for it.</p>

	<p><strong>Buy tickets online in advance</strong> to save time at the gate on busy days.</p>

	<p><strong>The Astrosphere is not to be missed.</strong> It sounds like a gimmick ("1970s laser dome"), but everyone who walks out is smiling. Give it five minutes.</p>

	<h2>Getting There</h2>

	<p>774 Portland Road (Route 1), Saco, ME 04072. From Saco Bay Hotel, it's less than a 5-minute drive south on Route 1. Parking is free and plentiful on site.</p>

	<div class="tip-box">
		<strong>Combine It with Palace Playland</strong>
		<p>Both parks are open through Labor Day and both are within a 15-minute drive of each other. A common guest strategy: spend the morning at Funtown (opens at 10:30 AM, great for families with younger kids), then drive to Old Orchard Beach in the afternoon for Palace Playland and the beach. Two parks, one day, no overlap.</p>
	</div>
